rchetta agrumata con finocchio, peperoncino e salvia","ingredients":[{"isHeader":true,"content":"Ingredients"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"2 Tbsp dried fennel seeds"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"½ - 1 Tbsp chilli flakes, to taste"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"1 orange, thin peelings of skin only"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"5 garlic cloves"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"6 fresh sage leaves"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"30 g coarse sea salt"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"30 - 60 g white wine, to taste"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"1250 g pork belly, boned, with rind"},{"isHeader":false,"content":"750 g pork loin"}],"nutrition":["per 1 portion","2145 kJ \/ 515 kcal","46.6 g","1.1 g","35.8 g"],"hintsAndTricks":["It may be necessary to trim the loin and\/or pork belly so that the belly can be rolled completely around the loin before tying.","Resting the joint uncovered in the fridge allows the skin to dry out and results in better crackling.","Adjust roasting times according to the total weight of the meat. A <b>3.5-4 kg<b> joint will take <b>3-4 hours<b> (160°C).","Also delicious served cold in sandwiches.","Traditionally porchetta was prepared using a whole deboned pig that was seasoned, rolled, and cooked on a pit over a wood-burning fire – a laborious process that meant it was a meal reserved for celebratory events where there would be large crowds to feed. Renowned as one of Italy’s best-loved dishes, porchetta is now so popular that it has been selected by the Italian Ministry of Agricultural, Food and Forestry Policy as one of a list of traditional Italian foods with cultural relevance."],"basicInfo":["medium","15m","10h 55m","8 portions"]}